		<h2 class="title"><span class="image-wrapper"><img height="45" alt="Yam pyramids" width="226" class="title" src="../../resources/net.databinder.components.RenderedLabel/da4c482f"/><span class="title">Yam pyramids</span></span></h2>
		<div class="byline"><span>
			<span>By <span class="alias">Leland</span>, <span>on February 26, 2006</span></span>
			<span id="id15f3" class="tags">
					{&nbsp;<span><a href="../../eat/tag/home%20cooking/#selected-tag"><span>home cooking</span></a></span>&nbsp;}
			</span>
		</span></div>
		<div><p>I made an ordinary dinner extraordinary last night with creative plating.</p>


	<p style="float:center"><img src="/pictures/rosemarychicken.jpg" alt="" /></p>


	<p>After seeing Jake&#8217;s pictures of the pyramids yesterday afternoon, I decided to build little pyramids of yams and garlic. I&#8217;m starting to wonder why people bother to eat regular potatoes. Ok, that&#8217;s stupid, of course potatoes have their merits. But yams are so cheap and sweet and versatile. I love them mashed, saut√©ed, and especially roasted with sea salt, herbs, and garlic. They are beautiful on the plate and on the tongue.</p>


	<p>Today I am working on <a href="http://www.epicurious.com/recipes/recipe_views/views/233545">flanken braised in ancho-chile sauce</a>, which we&#8217;ll eat tomorrow or Tuesday night. It&#8217;s no small task to prepare such fragrant ingredients when you&#8217;ve been hungover all morning, but I held my nose got it in the oven.</p></div>
